    term: 'Adapter',
    definition:
      'Adapters are an advanced method for making pre-trained AI models adaptable to new tasks without complete retraining.',
    long_definition:
      '## Adapter Technology in AI\n\n### Overview\nIn the realm of machine learning and artificial intelligence, **adapters** serve as pivotal components that bridge the gap between pre-trained models and new, domain-specific tasks. Traditionally, adapting a pre-trained model to a new task required extensive retraining, which consumed resources and time. However, with the introduction of adapters, this process has become significantly more efficient.\n\nAdapters function by adding small, trainable layers to the pre-trained architecture. These layers adjust the model\u2019s parameters only slightly, while maintaining the integrity of the original model\u2019s capabilities. This allows the core model to remain unchanged\u2014eliminating the need for complete retraining\u2014and focuses computational resources on fine-tuning just the new adapter layers.\n\n### Applications and Use Cases\n- **Natural Language Processing (NLP):** In NLP, adapters are frequently used to fine-tune models for tasks such as sentiment analysis, linguistic translation, and question answering.\n- **Computer Vision:** Adapters enable pre-trained vision models to adjust quickly to new visual tasks like object detection and classification in novel image datasets.\n- **Robotics:** By utilizing adapters, robots can be reprogrammed to perform a new set of tasks without extensive re-engineering of the existing learning mechanisms.\n\n### Benefits and Insights\n- **Resource Efficiency:** Using adapters can significantly reduce the computation and time required to adapt models to new tasks, leveraging the power of previously acquired data processing capabilities.\n- **Versatility:** A single pre-trained model can support a wide array of tasks simply by attaching different adapter layers specific to each task.\n- **Cost-Effective:** By avoiding the need to build a model from scratch for every new task, adapters cut down on financial resources otherwise spent on training and development.\n\nThe use of adapters accentuates the evolution of machine learning strategies, making way for more dynamic and responsive AI systems. This approach not only furthers technological advancement but also democratises AI application by lowering the barrier to entry in terms of expertise and computing power needed to harness complex AI models.',
    slug: 'adapter',
