    term: 'Active Learning',
    definition:
      'Active learning is a machine learning approach where the algorithm can interactively query a user or some other source to obtain new data points to improve the learning process.',
    long_definition:
      "## Overview\nActive learning is a type of machine learning in which the learning algorithm is able to interactively query the user or an external source to label new data points with the desired outputs. This approach is especially useful in scenarios where data acquisition can be costly or time-consuming.\n\n## Variations\n- **Pool-Based Sampling:** In this model, the algorithm maintains a pool of unlabeled data and selects the most informative samples from this pool for labeling.\n- **Stream-Based Selective Sampling:** Here, the system evaluates each incoming data point to decide whether it should be labeled or discarded, often used in real-time applications.\n- **Membership Query Synthesis:** In this case, the learner generates its own instance for labeling, which is typically applied in research or controlled environments.\n\n## Examples and Use Cases\n- **Healthcare:** Active learning can be used to improve diagnostic systems by efficiently selecting the most informative patient cases for labeling by medical experts, thus reducing the burden on clinicians.\n- **Autonomous Systems:** In autonomous vehicle development, active learning helps in prioritizing complex driving scenarios that are rare and require expert annotation.\n- **Natural Language Processing:** It can be applied in sentiment analysis where the model requests labels for the most ambiguous pieces of text to enhance the sentiment classifier's performance.\n\n## Notable Insights\n- **Cost-Efficiency:** Active learning can significantly reduce the cost of labeling data while maintaining or even improving model accuracy by focusing on the most informative samples.\n- **Human-in-the-Loop:** This approach often involves a human-in-the-loop setup, enabling more nuanced model improvements compared to fully automated systems.\n- **Data Diversity:** By selecting diverse and uncertain examples for labeling, active learning addresses class imbalance and enhances the model's generalization capability.",
