    long_definition:
      '## Overview of AI Agents\n### Definition and Purpose\nAI Agents are entities within artificial intelligence systems that engage in activities aimed at achieving specified goals with minimal direct human intervention. They are particularly instrumental in environments where constant human guidance is infeasible, operating independently to manage tasks that require complex decision-making and adaptability.\n\n### Variations in AI Agents\n- **Autonomous Agents:** These are systems entirely capable of making decisions and executing tasks without human input. Examples include robot vacuum cleaners and autonomous drones, which perform their duties based on pre-set objectives and sensory data.\n- **Tool-Using Agents:** Some AI agents are not fully autonomous but rely on large language models (LLMs) to make decisions. Such agents can call upon external utilities, APIs, or tools to complete specific functions. These systems combine autonomous decision-making with tool assistance, effectively bridging the gap between human oversight and complete autonomy.\n\n### Real-World Use Cases and Examples\nAI agents find application across a wide spectrum of industries, tailored to their specific capabilities:\n\n- **In Finance:** AI agents are used for automated trading, analyzing vast datasets to detect patterns and execute transactions more efficiently than human traders.\n- **Healthcare:** Agents help in patient monitoring by analyzing health data in real-time to facilitate proactive interventions.\n- **E-commerce:** Chatbots serve as customer service agents, autonomously handling consumer inquiries and issues through text interactions. [AI Chatbots for the Ecommerce Industry](https://docsbot.ai/industry/e-commerce) are a classic example of tool-using agents employed in such settings.\n\n### Further Insights\nThe capability distinction between tool-using and fully autonomous agents allows for a nuanced application in various fields, aligning with enterprise needs for scalability and effectiveness. An essential consideration is the ethical design and deployment of these agents, particularly in regard to decision-making authority and accountability, which necessitates ongoing discourse within the AI community.',
