    term: 'Auto-regressive model',
    definition:
      'An auto-regressive model is a type of statistical model used for analyzing and predicting time-series data by regressing the variable on its own lagged values.',
    long_definition:
      '## Understanding Auto-Regressive Models\nAuto-regressive (AR) models are used extensively in time series analysis to understand and predict future points in the series. The central concept behind these models is that they utilize the dependent relationship between an observation and a number of lagged observations.\n\n### Examples and Applications\nAuto-regressive models are widely utilized in fields such as economics for forecasting economic indicators, in environmental science to predict meteorological data, and in engineering for control processes.\n\n- **Economic Forecasting:** AR models are often employed in predicting stock market trends, where the historical price data provides insights into future movements.\n- **Environmental Science:** In meteorology, these models help in predicting temperature variations based on historical temperature data.\n\n### Insights and Limitations\nWhile AR models can be powerful, they come with limitations. They assume that the series are stationary, meaning that statistical properties such as the mean and variance remain constant over time. When the data is not stationary, transformations might be necessary to stabilize variance or achieve stationarity.\n\nA further understanding of AR models leads to their amalgamation with other models, such as moving average models, to form ARMA or ARIMA models, providing even more nuanced approaches to time series analysis.',
