    definition:
      'Automation refers to the use of technology to perform tasks with minimal human intervention.',
    long_definition:
      '## Overview\nAutomation is a technological advancement that seeks to minimize human intervention in various tasks and processes. It employs technologies like robotics, software, and computer systems to perform tasks that were previously carried out manually. This concept has revolutionized industries by enhancing productivity, reducing manual errors, and improving operational efficiency.\n\n### Types of Automation\n- **Fixed Automation:** This type of automation is characterized by high production volumes and is commonly used in manufacturing industries, such as automotive production lines. The equipment is specifically set up to perform a particular task, like assembly or material handling, and is not easily altered.\n- **Programmable Automation:** Designed for variable production volumes, programmable automation allows for the configuration of robotic machinery and equipment. This is frequently employed in batch processes where the production runs can be changed from one product to another.\n- **Flexible Automation:** Also known as "soft" automation, this type can handle varying types of operations, such as in a manufacturing line producing a range of products with minimal setup time between them.\n\n### Examples and Use Cases\n- **Manufacturing:** Automation in manufacturing often involves both programmable and flexible automation systems, enabling efficient production runs while allowing for product variations.\n- **Customer Support:** Through [AI chatbots](https://docsbot.ai/article/chatbots-for-everyone-openais-gpts-and-their-limitations), companies automate routine customer inquiries, freeing up human agents to handle more complex problems.\n- **Data Processing:** Automation tools allow for massive datasets to be processed without human intervention, streamlining operations in big data analytics.\n\n### Notable Insights\n- Automation has significantly reshaped job roles, leading to evolving career paths where humans work alongside automated systems to enhance productivity and innovation.\n- The implementation of automation technologies requires a thorough analysis on cost versus benefit, as initial setup can be costly but may lead to substantial long-term savings.\n- With the rise of automation, there are growing ethical considerations regarding job displacement and a need for strategies that reskill the existing workforce to collaborate successfully with technology.',
