    term: 'Clustering',
    definition:
      'Clustering is the process of grouping a set of objects in such a way that objects in the same group (or cluster) are more similar to each other than to those in other groups.',
    long_definition:
      '## Understanding Clustering\nAt its core, clustering is an unsupervised machine learning technique that involves organizing data points into groups based on similar characteristics. Unlike classification which is supervised, clustering does not rely on predefined labels; instead, it seeks to discover patterns or structures within data on its own. This method is utilized in various domains, including data mining, image analysis, and customer segmentation to enhance the extraction of meaningful information.\n\n### Methods and Techniques\n- **K-Means Clustering:** One of the most popular and simple clustering algorithms that partition data into `K` clusters, each represented by the mean of its points. It is particularly known for its speed and efficiency on large datasets.\n- **Hierarchical Clustering:** Builds a tree of clusters. It can be either agglomerative (bottom-up) or divisive (top-down), offering a more detailed group relationship.\n- **DBSCAN (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise):** Focuses on grouping together points closely packed together while marking those that lie alone in low-density areas as outliers.\n\n### Applications and Use Cases\nClustering can significantly enhance technologies like **[DocsBot AI](https://docsbot.ai/)** by grouping similar questions. This not only increases the efficiency of information retrieval in chatbots but also boosts their recall capability in a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) framework. By identifying core topics from user interactions, clustering aids in generating insightful analytics reports, revealing prevalent themes and user concerns.\n\n### Notable Insights\n- In content creation and management, clustering establishes coherent topic clusters using embeddings. This ensures content aligns with user interests and improves navigation efficiency.\n- Clustering goes beyond simple data grouping by helping in market segmentation, anomaly detection, and even document classification, providing a powerful tool for businesses to understand and optimize their strategy.\n- **[RAG-Fusion](https://docsbot.ai/article/advanced-rag-techniques-multiquery-and-rank-fusion)**: By employing sophisticated clustering techniques, RAG systems enhance their ability to manage variations in data queries, ensuring high recall and precision in dynamic user interactions.',
