    term: 'Conversational UI',
    definition:
      'Conversational UI (CUI) refers to user interfaces that allow interaction through text or voice communication, providing a more personal and fluid user experience compared to traditional interfaces.',
    long_definition:
      "### Overview\nConversational User Interfaces (CUIs) are designed to facilitate interaction between humans and machines via conversational methods such as text or speech. Unlike traditional UIs, which rely on visual elements such as buttons and icons that users manipulate directly, CUIs harness natural language processing to engage users in a dialogue, making interactions more intuitive and human-like.\n\n### Key Differences\n- **Interaction Mode:**  \n  - **Traditional UIs:** Users engage by clicking, typing, and interacting with visual elements.  \n  - **CUIs:** Interaction occurs through conversation\u2014either typed or spoken\u2014which can mimic human-to-human communication.\n\n- **User Experience:**  \n  - **Traditional UIs:** Often require users to adapt their needs to the options provided by the interface.  \n  - **CUIs:** Seek to adapt the interface responses to the user\u2019s needs in a dynamic and personalized fashion, potentially enhancing user satisfaction.\n\n### Applications and Use Cases\nOne of the most prominent applications of CUIs is in [customer support](https://docsbot.ai/article/ai-helpdesk-assistants). CUIs can quickly address users' inquiries by simulating conversational interactions, which can significantly speed up the process of troubleshooting and problem-solving. These interfaces also find applications in [product onboarding](https://docsbot.ai/article/using-ai-chatbot-uis-for-product-onboarding), where CUIs can guide users through software and app functionalities via a conversational walkthrough. This method simplifies learning and adaptation phases, especially for novice users who benefit from a more narrative-style guidance.\n\n### Insights and Future Directions\nThe development of CUI technology continues to advance, driven by improvements in AI and natural language processing. As CUIs evolve, further seamless integration with daily human activities is expected, such as being embedded in various devices and environments that support real-time conversations. Moreover, CUIs\u2019 potential to bridge gaps in accessibility, language barriers, and personalization paves the way for more inclusive user experiences in technology applications.",
