    term: 'Imagen',
    definition:
      'Imagen is a text-to-image diffusion model developed by Google Research that leverages frozen text encoders to generate high-quality images from textual descriptions.',
    long_definition:
      '## Overview\nImagen is a state-of-the-art text-to-image generative model that is trained to convert textual descriptions into highly detailed images. Developed by Google Research, Imagen builds upon diffusion models, which are a class of generative models that aim to gradually transform a simple noise distribution into a complex data distribution, such as images.\n\n## Characteristics\n- **Text Encoders:** Imagen utilizes a frozen text encoder to interpret the semantics of the input text. This allows it to capture nuanced descriptions and faithfully render these into images.\n- **Diffusion Process:** The model follows a diffusion process that starts with noise, gradually refining it into a coherent image.\n\n## Examples and Use Cases\n- **Creative Design:** Artists and designers can use Imagen to create visual representations of concepts, helping to illustrate ideas that are described through text.\n- **Content Generation:** It can be incorporated into advertising to generate images for product mockups based on short textual descriptions, thus speeding up the creative process.\n\n## Insights\nImagen has set new benchmarks in text-to-image generation, notably surpassing many previous models in terms of image fidelity and correspondence to textual inputs. However, like many AI generation models, it faces challenges related to the ethical considerations of content generation and potential biases inherent within the training data.',
