    definition:
      "Llama refers to Meta's series of open-source large language models, characterized by their open weights, including Llama versions 2, 3.1, and 3.2.",
    long_definition:
      "### Overview\nLlama is a significant development in the realm of large language models (LLMs), spearheaded by Meta (formerly Facebook). This open-source initiative offers a set of models with open weights, meaning that developers and researchers have access to and can modify these models directly. Such accessibility lays the groundwork for innovation and collaboration in the AI community, removing barriers typically imposed by proprietary systems.\n\n### Versions and Innovations\n- **Llama 2:** Marked the initial wave of open LLMs under this initiative, setting a precedent in the industry by allowing open access to its model weights.\n- **Llama 3.1 and 3.2:** These updates brought enhanced capabilities, expanded comprehension, and computational efficiency, primarily focusing on improving language understanding and generation.\n\n### Use Cases and Applications\nThe open design of the Llama models has sparked a wide range of applications:\n- **Research:** Facilitates academic and industry researchers to experiment with and extend language models without rebuilding from scratch.\n- **Education:** Provides a practical tool for institutions teaching AI principles, offering hands-on experience with an industry-grade language model.\n- **Commercial Applications:** Companies can embed Llama models into chatbots or other natural language processing solutions, increasing their AI toolkit flexibility.\n\n### Notable Insights\nThe open-source strategy embraced by Meta for Llama creates a transparent development environment, encouraging ethical AI practices and sharing insights that otherwise might remain proprietary. The improvements seen in [Llama 3.2](https://docsbot.ai/article/exploring-llama-3-2-a-landmark-update-with-vision-capabilities), for example, reflect ongoing efforts to refine and enhance large language models' practical utility, making AI more accessible and tailored to diverse applications.",
