    term: 'Multimodal',
    definition:
      'A multimodal model refers to a large language model (LLM) that is trained on multiple types of modalities beyond just text, including audio, video, and images.',
    long_definition:
      '### Overview\nMultimodal models represent a significant advancement in the field of artificial intelligence and machine learning. These models are trained to process and interpret data from various modalities\u2014text, audio, image, and video\u2014simultaneously. The core advantage of multimodal systems is their ability to combine information from different sources to generate insights that were previously unattainable with single-modality models.\n\n### Characteristics\n- **Integration of Modalities:** Multimodal models bring together visual, auditory, and textual data, allowing them to understand content in a more holistic manner. For instance, when analyzing a video, a multimodal model can understand the spoken words (audio), recognize objects in the footage (video), and even read text displayed within the scene (text).\n- **Complex Understanding:** These models can perform tasks such as image captioning, video semantic analysis, and speech recognition, all by leveraging the interconnectedness of different data types.\n\n### Examples and Applications\n- **Image and Video Analysis:** In the realm of visual data, multimodal models can generate detailed image descriptions, similar to tools like a [free AI image description generator](https://docsbot.ai/tools/image-description-generator), which helps in creating alt texts for accessibility.\n- **Interactive Systems:** In virtual assistants and customer service environments, multimodal bots can interpret customer queries that include images or voice inputs, providing a more interactive and natural user experience.\n- **Healthcare Imaging:** In sectors like healthcare, multimodal models assist in diagnostic tasks by combining imaging data like X-rays and MRIs with patient information.\n\n### Challenges and Considerations\n- **Integration Complexity:** Building a system that effectively integrates multiple data modalities can be challenging due to the diversity and complexity of data.\n- **Computational Resources:** Multimodal models often require significant computational resources for training and deployment, which can be a limiting factor for some organizations.\n\nOverall, multimodal models represent a significant leap toward more intuitive and capable AI systems that closely mimic human perception by integrating data from various senses.',
