    term: 'Natural language processing',
    definition:
      'Natural language processing (NLP) is a branch of artificial intelligence that focuses on enabling computers to understand, interpret, and respond to human language in a way that is both meaningful and useful.',
    long_definition:
      '## Overview\nNatural language processing (NLP) spans several disciplines, including computer science, linguistics, and artificial intelligence, aiming to bridge the gap between human communication and computer understanding. NLP focuses specifically on how to program computers to process and analyze large amounts of natural language data.\n\n### Key Components of NLP\n- **Tokenization**: Splitting text into words or phrases called tokens.\n- **Part-of-Speech Tagging**: Identifying the grammatical categories of words.\n- **Named Entity Recognition (NER)**: Recognizing and classifying key entities in the text into predefined categories.\n- **Sentiment Analysis**: Determining the emotional tone behind the text.\n\n### Application Examples\n- **Virtual Assistants**: Tools like [Siri](https://docsbot.ai/article/new-iframe-widget-embed-and-cloud-source-types), Alexa, and Google Assistant rely heavily on NLP to understand and respond to user commands.\n- **Chatbots**: Many businesses use NLP-powered chatbots to interact with customers as a first line of support.\n- **Language Translation**: Applications like Google Translate use NLP to convert text from one language to another while attempting to preserve its original meaning and context.\n\n### Insights and Challenges\nNLP technologies are continuously evolving and face challenges such as understanding context, managing idioms, slang, and handling noisy data from real-world environments. Researchers work on methods like neural networks and deep learning to improve accuracy and ensure processes are more nuanced and human-like in their responses.\n\nMoreover, with the advancement of NLP technologies, ethical considerations regarding data privacy and the potential for bias in AI models have become more prominent. Careful evaluation and training approaches are essential to mitigate these concerns and enhance the responsible use of NLP in various fields.',
