      'Structured knowledge refers to the organized and catalogued form of data and information that allows for easy retrieval, analysis, and utilization.',
    long_definition:
      '## Overview\nStructured knowledge represents data that is organized in a standardized format such as databases, spreadsheets, or knowledge graphs, enabling machines and humans to process and interpret it efficiently. This organization helps in providing clear context and relationships between data elements, making it a crucial component for various applications.\n\n### Key Characteristics\n- **Standardized Format:** Structured knowledge often uses specific forms like tables, charts, or schemas that are easily readable by machines, enhancing computational efficiency.\n- **Hierarchy and Relationships:** It typically includes hierarchical relationships which help in understanding the linkages and dependencies between different pieces of information.\n- **Data Types:** Structured data includes types such as strings, numbers, and dates, which can be neatly stored with high retrieval speed and accuracy.\n\n### Examples and Use Cases\n- **Knowledge Graphs:** Utilized by companies like Google and Microsoft, these graphs link information about entities and their relationships, offering enhanced search and recommendation capabilities.\n- **Relational Databases:** Used in business applications for managing customer information, financial data, and sales records, allowing for complex queries and report generation.\n- **Metadata Collection:** Libraries use structured metadata to catalog books, ensuring they are easily searchable by title, author, subject, and other identifiers.\n\n### Notable Insights\n- Structured knowledge significantly boosts the efficiency of AI systems by providing clear, actionable data inputs, facilitating tasks such as machine learning model training and data analysis.\n- It contrasts with unstructured data, like free text, which lacks a predefined format, although advances in [AI technologies](https://docsbot.ai/articles) are integrating methods to derive structure from unstructured data through techniques like [natural language processing](https://docsbot.ai/article/natural-language-processing). \n- The reliance on structured knowledge is integral in fields such as data science, business analytics, and [AI chatbots](https://docsbot.ai/article/chatbots-for-everyone-openais-gpts-and-their-limitations) where data precision and accessibility directly influence outcome quality.',
