      'Tools in the context of AI are external functions or APIs that a language model (LLM) can access to perform various tasks based on its instructions.',
    long_definition:
      '### Understanding Tools in AI\nIn the realm of artificial intelligence, particularly with regard to language models, "tools" refer to the auxiliary functions or interfaces that these models can use to enhance their capabilities. These tools provide additional functionalities such as accessing external data, processing inputs in specialized ways, or influencing an environment beyond the model\'s standard operational scope.\n\n### Application and Use Cases\n- **Integration with APIs:** Language models can utilize tools in the form of APIs to gather real-time data or execute actions outside their immediate dataset, such as performing calculations, fetching web data, or even controlling IoT devices.\n- **Automating Processes:** Tools enable models to automate various workflows, such as summarizing a video using a [Free AI YouTube Video Summarizer](https://docsbot.ai/tools/ai-youtube-summarizer) or generating content based on specific user queries.\n\n### Examples\n- **Data Processing:** Suppose an AI tool functions as an image analyzer; a language model could use this tool to describe images and improve accessibility, as seen in similar capabilities like [Free AI Image Description Generator](https://docsbot.ai/tools/image-description-generator).\n- **Enhancing Interactions:** Language models can be empowered through integrations with chat platforms, using [DocsBot AI](https://docsbot.ai/) to create sophisticated, documentation-based chatbots.\n\n### Notable Insights\nThe inclusion of tools significantly expands the functional landscape of language models, allowing for more dynamic and contextually enriched responses. This toolkit approach is a hallmark of advanced AI systems today, blending computational power with versatile functionality, ensuring both adaptability and efficiency across different sectors and applications.',
