    term: 'Uncertainty Quantification',
    definition:
      'Uncertainty quantification (UQ) is a field of study that deals with the impact of uncertainty in mathematical modeling and simulation of physical systems.',
    long_definition:
      "## Overview\nUncertainty Quantification (UQ) is an essential process in applied mathematics and engineering that involves predicting the uncertainty in scientific simulations and models. It focuses on determining how reliable a given computational model is by assessing the impact of uncertainties in the inputs, parameters, and even in the model's structure itself.\n\n### Variations\n- **Parametric Uncertainty:** Arises when the parameters in a model cannot be known with precision. For example, material properties like elasticity might have variability within a manufacturing process.\n- **Model Uncertainty:** Associated with the approximation in a mathematical model. Even with perfect input, the discrepancy between reality and the model can lead to uncertainty.\n- **Stochastic Uncertainty:** Pertains to inherent randomness in systems such as turbulent flows or market fluctuations.\n\n### Examples and Use Cases\n- **Engineering Design:** In aerospace engineering, UQ helps in designing components that must perform reliably under uncertain conditions, such as varying flight loads or atmospheric conditions.\n- **Environmental Modeling:** In climate modeling, UQ is used to project future climates and assess the likely impacts of different policy decisions.\n- **Financial Modeling:** UQ helps in managing risks by assessing the uncertainty in financial predictions due to market volatility.\n\n### Notable Insights\n- UQ tools often utilize techniques such as Monte Carlo simulations or polynomial chaos expansions to propagate uncertainties through models.\n- Effective UQ can not only improve the reliability of predictions but also guide decision-making processes by quantifying risks associated with uncertain outcomes.\n- Advances in UQ are increasingly reliant on [machine learning](https://docsbot.ai/ai-terms-glossary/term/machine-learning) approaches to model and adaptively refine predictions as more data becomes available.",
