    term: 'Variational Autoencoder (VAE)',
    definition:
      'A Variational Autoencoder is a type of artificial neural network that learns efficient representations of data, leveraging probability to define and train its encoder and decoder components.',
    long_definition:
      "## Overview\nA Variational Autoencoder (VAE) is a generative model that captures the underlying structures of data through probabilistic techniques. Unlike traditional autoencoders, VAEs are capable of generating new data that resembles the input data, making them widely used in applications such as image synthesis and anomaly detection.\n\n### Primary Components\n- **Encoder:** Maps input data into latent space, generating two outputs: a mean vector and a standard deviation vector. These parameters define the probability distribution of the latent variables.\n- **Decoder:** Uses latent variables sampled from the distribution defined by the encoder to reconstruct data.\n\n### Variational Approach\nThe 'variational' in VAE denotes the use of variational inference\u2014a method in machine learning to estimate the posterior distributions. Instead of mapping each input to a single point in the latent space, VAEs map inputs to a distribution, allowing for robust data representation with stochastic neural networks.\n\n### Applications and Use Cases\n- **Image Generation:** VAEs are prevalent in generating realistically synthesized images through their ability to map and sample complex data distributions.\n- **Anomaly Detection:** By learning the distribution of normal data, VAEs can identify outliers or anomalies as data points that do not conform to this learned distribution.\n- **Dimensionality Reduction:** VAE's probabilistic encoding-decoding mechanism aids in reducing data dimensions while maintaining the essential features, akin to [training a chatbot from complex sources](https://docsbot.ai/documentation/doc/training-a-chatbot-from-raw-data-csv).\n\n### Advantages\n- VAEs ensure smooth interpolation between data points, which is valuable in various computer vision applications.\n- They enable the sampling of different representations from the same input data, contributing to robust feature extraction capabilities.\n",
    slug: 'variational-autoencoder-vae',
    letter: 'v',
    question: 'What is a Variational Autoencoder (VAE)?',
